        </div> <!-- #brief_1 -->

        <div id="brief_2" class="section block-warning align-c-xs-max">
          <div class="container">
            <div class="row row-table">
              <div class="col-sm-6 m-b-60-xs-max p-r-60-md-min">
                <div class="col-inner clearfix">
                  <%= image_tag("landing-2.jpg", class: "img-responsive float-l-sm-min m-x-auto-xs-max", data: {sr: "left"}) %>
                </div>
              </div>
              <div class="col-sm-6">
                <div class="col-inner">
                  <div class="section-heading">
                    <h2>How does coding progress from K-5 and beyond?</h2>
                  </div> <!-- .section-heading -->
                  <div class="section-content">
                    <p>
                      Teaching coding in elementary school is similar to teaching reading, in that grades K-2 lay a foundation on which grades 3-5 can build on.
                      In reading education we teach phonics and fluency in younger grade, and we teach start reading longer books in 3-5. With coding, the idea
                      is to build foundational skills in younger grades and then start to actually build stuff in older grades.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                      The end goal is to be able to build stuff in Scratch by the end of elementary school, <a target='_blank' href='https://scratch.mit.edu/projects/77529740/'>like this</a>.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                      <ul>
                      <li>
                        <b>PreK - 1: </b>Teachers integrate computational thinking into existing class lessons,  <a target='_blank' href='https://studio.code.org/s/course1/stage/12/puzzle/1'>such as this</a>.
                      </li>
                      <li>
                        <b>2: </b>Students explore Scratch Jr activities,  <a target='_blank' href='https://medium.com/scratchfoundation-blog/10-things-to-try-right-now-with-your-child-on-scratch-and-scratchjr-defd7f8ad0d1'>like these</a>.
                      </li>
                      <li>
                        The activities are <a target='_blank' href='https://hourofcode.com/us/learn'>here</a>. You can filter by
                        age, grade, experience level, and many other things.
                      </li>
                      <li>
                        My favorite are the Social Studies and Language Arts activities!
                      </li>
                      <li>
                        Use those activities above and try it out! You have 10 minutes. This is your DO NOW!
                        Can't one to choose? Try this one <a target='_blank' href='https://game.kodable.com/hour-of-code'>here</a>.
                      </li>
                    </ul>
                    </p>
                  </div> <!-- .section-content -->
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div> <!-- #brief_2 -->

